nkte auf der Opposition "perfektiv : imperfektiv" (einschließlich Aorist, Imperfekt, Prozessiv) und auf dem "Perfekt". Daneben werden "Proximativ" und "Ingressiv" sowie die Frage der Relevanz aspektsensitiver Verbklassen auch für (aktionale) Verbalperiphrasen behandelt. Die Daten stammen aus Sprachen sehr verschiedener Gruppen und Typen.  aThis collection examines the influence of lexical meaning on the functions of verb aspect. A systematic distinction is made between grammatical aspect and aspect-sensitive verb-classes (Aktionsarten) defined in terms of the boundary features or phase structures of what they refer to. Among the aspect categories discussed, emphasis is given to the completive/non-perfective opposition (including aorist, imperfect, progressive) and the 'perfect' form. In addition there is discussion of the 'proximative' and the 'ingressive' and the question of the relevance of aspect-sensitive verb-classes for (actional) verb periphrases. The data are taken from languages of very different groups and types.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxAspectvCongresses. 0aLexicologyvCongresses. 4aAspekt ‹Linguistik›. 4aKongress. 4aKonstanz ‹1995›. 4aWortschatz. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBickel, Balthasar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreu, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreu, Walter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChapado Chorro, Μ. Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCsató, Éva Ágnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrolc, Ursula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardenghi, Monica,